  <refsection xml:id="printf-description">
    <title>Description</title>
    <para>The <function>printf</function> family of functions produces output according to a
    <parameter>format</parameter> string. The <function>printf</function> function writes output to
    <systemitem class="resource">stdout</systemitem>, the standard output stream;
    <function>fprintf</function> writes to the given <parameter>stream</parameter>;
    <function>sprintf</function> writes to the character string <parameter>str</parameter>.</para>

    <para>The format string is a character string composed of zero or more directives:
    <indexterm>
      <primary>printf</primary>
      <secondary>format specifiers</secondary>
    </indexterm>
    ordinary characters (not <literal>%</literal>), which are copied unchanged to the output
    stream; and conversion specifications.</para>

    <note>
      <title>Security Warning</title>
      <para>Never pass user-supplied strings as the <parameter>format</parameter> argument.
      Use <userinput>printf("%s", user_string)</userinput> instead of
      <computeroutput>printf(user_string)</computeroutput>.</para>
    </note>

    <example>
      <title>Basic Usage</title>
      <programlisting language="c" linenumbering="numbered" startinglinenumber="1">
#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main(void) {
    printf("Hello, %s! You are %d years old.\n", <co xml:id="co-name"/>"World", 42<co xml:id="co-age"/>);
    return 0;
}
      </programlisting>
      <calloutlist>
        <callout arearefs="co-name">
          <para>The <literal>%s</literal> specifier formats a string argument.</para>
        </callout>
        <callout arearefs="co-age">
          <para>The <literal>%d</literal> specifier formats an integer argument.</para>
        </callout>
      </calloutlist>
    </example>

    <variablelist>
      <title>Common Format Specifiers</title>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><literal>%d</literal>, <literal>%i</literal></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>Print an <type>int</type> as a signed decimal number.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><literal>%s</literal></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>Print a <type>char *</type> as a null-terminated string.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
      <varlistentry>
        <term><literal>%f</literal></term>
        <listitem>
          <para>Print a <type>double</type> in fixed-point notation.</para>
        </listitem>
      </varlistentry>
    </variablelist>

